## 
## data:  tab

library(epitools)
oddsratio(tab)

## $measure
##         odds ratio with 95% C.I.

## $p.value
##         two-sided
##          midp.exact  fisher.exact chi.square
##   Male           NA            NA         NA
##   Female          0 1.073602e-170  2.12e-168

## $correction
## [1] FALSE
## 
## attr(,"method")
## [1] "median-unbiased estimate & mid-p exact CI"
ci95.p <- function(tab, cix){
       xx <- apply(tab, 1, function(x){prop.test(x[cix], sum(x), correct=TRUE)})
       phat <- lapply(xx, function(x){x$estimate})
       phat.ci <- lapply(xx, function(x){x$conf.int})
       res <- matrix(NA, nrow=length(phat), ncol=3)
       colnames(res) <- c("phat", "lcl", "ucl"); rownames(res) <- names(phat)
       for(i in 1:nrow(res)){
             res[i,] <- c(phat[[i]], phat.ci[[i]])
             }
       res
       }
bplot.prop <- function(tab, cix, xnames, colr="grey", ylabel, prop=TRUE){
      if(prop==TRUE){res <- data.frame(ci95.p(tab, cix))}
      if(prop==FALSE){res <- data.frame(ci95.p(tab, cix))*100}
      bp <- barplot(res$phat, xlab="", names=xnames, ylab=ylabel, ylim=c(0,max(res)))
      points(bp, res$phat, pch=16)
      segments(x0=bp, x1=bp, y0=res$lcl, y1=res$ucl, lwd=2)
      print(res)
      }
bplot.prop(tab, cix="Yes", xnames=c("Male", "Female"), ylabel="Percentage experiencing depression", prop=FALSE)
